******
[2]
Date: Thu 28 Jun 2012
Source: Cafe Fuerte, Hablemos Press report [in Spanish, machine trans., edited]
http://cafefuerte.com/cuba/noticias-de-cuba/sociedad/1960-dos-muertos-por-colera-en-el-oriente-de-cuba


At least 2 people died and more than 50 remain hospitalized in the town of Manzanillo, in eastern Cuba, where authorities decreed a quarantine at the Provincial Clinical and Surgical Hospital "Celia Sanchez Manduley". Police and state security agents guard the medical center, according to testimony given by residents in the cities of Manzanillo and Bayamo.

Although the government has maintained total silence and the news has not spread in official media, the medical situation seems rather complicated.

"At least 2 deaths have been reported and the hospital cannot cope, the aisles are full of stretchers with patients... ...already more than 50 people, including children and adults hospitalized with the disease," [says MCF, a resident] of Manzanillo. The identity of the deceased was not reported, although both were adults.

MCF said the outbreak is stronger in the communities of La Pesquera, Las Novilla, and La Vuelta el Cano, who have been quarantined by the authorities. All medical personnel have been mobilized to Manzanillo.

YGJ, who lives in the nearby city of Bayamo, claims she learned of the outbreak of the disease while visiting Manzanillo on 26 Jun 2012. "In the hospital Celia Sanchez hospital security staff were replaced by police officers and state security agents, to prevent information from leaving the hospital," she said.

A source connected to a government agency confirmed the reports of cholera in the area. On the afternoon of 28 Jun 2012, the popular program "Frecuencia 12" of the Granma local television abruptly reported an outbreak of diarrheal disease in the province, but gave no details of the affected areas.

[byline: Calixto R Martinez]

