******
[3]
Date: Fri 29 Jun 2012
Source: El Nuevo Herald, Cuba (Miami) [in Spanish, machine trans., summ. & edited]
http://www.elnuevoherald.com/2012/06/29/1240443/brote-de-colera-en-oriente-de.html


At least 2 dead and more than 100 people have been hospitalized as a result of a cholera outbreak in the Cuban city of Manzanillo, Granma province. The medical emergency began in the middle of this week [week of 25 Jun 2012] in the localities of La Pesquera and La Vuelta el Cano. Cuban government officials have not spoken officially about the situation.

"We have suspended the street sales of drinks and have been told that police have closed several restaurants as a precautionary measure," said Roberto de Jesus Guerra, director of Hablemos Press news agency, based in Havana.

Sources consulted by El Nuevo Herald confirmed that authorities ordered a state of "quarantine" to prevent the spread of the disease.

The Provincial Clinical and Surgical Hospital "Celia Sanchez Manduley" where most of those affected are hospitalized, is guarded by state security agents and police officers, said De Jesus.

The cholera outbreak in the eastern part of the island surprised locals and raised questions in Miami about how an outbreak of a disease, believed to have been controlled in Cuba, began. A hypothesis on the health emergency did not rule out the possibility that this was caused by contagion from the group of volunteers, doctors, and aide workers who served in Haiti. Recently a group of 119 health professionals -- the Cuban Medical Brigade (BMC) -- returned to the island after having completed an assistance mission in Port-au-Prince.

The exiled Cuban doctor Julio Cesar Alfonso, chief executive of Solidarity Without Borders, said the possibility that the source of infection was generated among the group of Cuban volunteers in Haiti "can not be ruled out".

"In any case it very strange because a case of cholera has not been reported in Cuba for a long time," said Alfonso.

[byline: Juan Carlos Chavez]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[ProMED-mail awaits additional information regarding this outbreak thought to be cholera.

Cases of cholera have been imported into the USA from Haiti without spread as developed countries with adequate clean water do not easily promote an outbreak.

The sanitary conditions in the southern area of Cuba where the outbreak is occurring are not clear. - Mod.LL

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Cuba can be seen at http://healthmap.org/r/2Gla. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
